tspan.tspan: This method is used by product teams to prioritize product
features by ranking features and calculating a score by four
factors: Reach, Impact, Confidence and Effort. This method is
used to rank features and calculate a score from these four
factors to help in prioritization. This can help the team decide
what design and development work to focus its efforts.
01. Pick Features
This can either be done by the project lead ahead of time or
together as a team. List them up in random order. Feel free to
do as many as is realistic by duplicating the feature rows.
02. Reach
Measured in the number of users within a specific time period.
who will be affected by the feature. This period can be, for
example, users per quarter or transactions per month.
03. Impact
How much value a feature can generate. Value is often a bit
subjective, but it’s best if we focus on value to users and
importance to the business.
04. Confidence
Helps you to factor in how much an idea is supported by data
or how much it comes from your “gut feeling”. If you have a
great idea for a big feature, but it’s not supported by any
research, then it helps you balance out your enthusiasm in the
equation.
05. Effort
How much time it will require from all members of your team
(including research, design and development) to deliver the
feature. It’s best to use man months per team member.
06. Calculating RICE
RICE is used to compare features and projects within a single
organization or department, not between companies. With this
in mind, it’s important to keep the scoring consistent over time.
Based on the results, reorder the features by highest to lowest
score and priority.
